{"title_page": "Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=August 2019}}{{short description|March 2018 scandal involving personal data mining for political purposes}}\n{{Short description|Scandal involving unconsented use of personal information on Facebook for political advertising.}}\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica and Facebook.jpg|thumb|A user of the Cambridge Analytica and Facebook product. ]]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\nThe '''Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal''' was a major scandal in early 2018 where [[Cambridge Analytica]] harvested the personal data of millions of people's [[Facebook]] profiles without their consent and used it for [[Political Advertising|political advertising]]. The scandal has been described as a watershed moment in the public understanding of personal data and precipitated a 17% fall in Facebook's share price and calls for tighter regulation of tech companies' use of personal data.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2018/04/09/why-is-mark-zuckerberg-testifying-in-congress|title=Why is Mark Zuckerberg testifying in Congress?|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-13|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nA data scientist at [[Cambridge University]], [[Aleksandr Kogan]], was hired by Cambridge Analytica, to develop an app called \"This Is Your Digital Life\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hern|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/10/facebook-notify-users-data-harvested-cambridge-analytica|title=How to check whether Facebook shared your data with Cambridge Analytica|date=April 10, 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>{{when}} (sometimes stylized as \"thisisyourdigitallife\").<ref name=\"guardian original4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election|title=Revealed: 50 million Facebook profiles harvested for Cambridge Analytica in major data breach|last1=Graham-Harrison|first1=Emma|last2=Cadwalladr|first2=Carole|date=March 17, 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318001541/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election|archive-date=March 18, 2018|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC News3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-05/facebook-raises-cambridge-analytica-estimates/9620652|title=Facebook says 300,000 Australians may have had their data 'improperly shared'|date=April 5, 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=May 17, 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref> He provided the app to Cambridge Analytica,<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> and Cambridge Analytica in turn arranged an [[informed consent]] process for research in which several hundred thousand Facebook users would agree to complete a survey for payment that was only for academic use.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite news|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/07/the-great-british-brexit-robbery-hijacked-democracy|title=The great British Brexit robbery: how our democracy was hijacked|date=2017-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> However, Facebook allowed this app not only to collect personal information from survey respondents but also from respondents\u2019 Facebook friends.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> In this way, Cambridge Analytica acquired data from millions of Facebook users.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" />\n\nThe illicit harvesting of [[personal data]] by Cambridge Analytica was first reported in December 2015 by Harry Davies, a journalist for ''[[The Guardian]]''. He reported that Cambridge Analytica was working for United States Senator [[Ted Cruz]] using data harvested from millions of people's Facebook accounts without their consent.<ref name=\"guardian December 20155\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data|title=Ted Cruz campaign using firm that harvested data on millions of unwitting Facebook users|last1=Davies|first1=Harry|date=December 11, 2015|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216175150/http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data|archive-date=February 16, 2016|df=}}</ref> Facebook refused to comment on the story other than to say it was investigating.{{citation needed}} Further reports followed in the Swiss publication ''Das Magazin'' by Hannes Grasseger and Mikael Krogerus (December 2016) (later translated and published by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''),{{citation needed}} [[Carole Cadwalladr]] in ''The Guardian'' (starting in February 2017){{citation needed}} and Mattathias Schwartz in ''[[The Intercept]]'' (March 2017).{{citation needed}} Facebook refused to comment on the claims in any of the articles.{{citation needed}}\n\nThe scandal finally erupted in March 2018 with the emergence of a whistleblower, an ex-Cambridge Analytica employee [[Christopher Wylie]]. He had been an anonymous source for an article in 2017 in ''[[The Observer]]'' by Cadwalladr, headlined \"The Great British [[Brexit]] Robbery\".<ref name=\":04\" /> This article went viral but was disbelieved in some quarters, prompting skeptical responses in ''[[The New York Times]]'' among others.{{citation needed}} Cadwalladr worked with Wylie for a year to coax him to come forward as a whistleblower.{{citation needed}} She later brought in [[Channel 4 News]] in the UK and ''The New York Times'' due to legal threats against ''The Guardian'' and ''The Observer'' by Cambridge Analytica.{{citation needed}}\n\nThe three news organisations{{which}} published simultaneously on March 17, 2018, and caused a huge public outcry.{{citation needed}} More than $100 billion was knocked off Facebook's market capitalization in days{{citation needed}} and politicians in the US and UK demanded answers from Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]]. The scandal eventually led to him agreeing to testify in front of the [[United States Congress]].{{citation needed}}\n\n==Characteristics of the data==\n\n==== Numbers ====\n''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', ''The New York Times'', and ''The Observer'' reported that the data-set had included information on 50 million Facebook users.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/facebook-exposed-87-million-users-to-cambridge-analytica/|title=Facebook Exposed 87 Million Users to Cambridge Analytica|work=Wired|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT original4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matthew|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|date=March 17, 2018|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317131953/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|archive-date=March 17, 2018|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole|df=}}</ref> While Cambridge Analytica claimed it had only collected 30 million Facebook user profiles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/facebook-send-cambridge-analytica-data-use-notices-monday-n863811|title=Facebook to send Cambridge Analytica data-use notices to 87 million users today|date=April 9, 2018|work=NBC News|accessdate=April 9, 2018|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Facebook later confirmed that it actually had data on potentially over 87 million users,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1245049/the-cambridge-analytica-scandal-affected-87-million-people-facebook-says/|title=The Cambridge Analytica scandal affected 87 million people, Facebook says|last1=Kozlowska|first1=Hanna|date=April 4, 2018|website=Quartz|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> with 70.6 million of those people from the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1245355/outside-us-philippines-saw-most-facebook-user-data-go-to-cambridge-analytica/|title=Outside US, Philippines saw most Facebook user data go to Cambridge Analytica|last1=Horwitz|first1=Josh|date=April 5, 2018|website=Quartz|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> Facebook estimated that [[California]] was the most affected U.S. state, with 6.7 million impacted users, followed by [[Texas]], with 5.6 million, and [[Florida]], with 4.3 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nieva|first=Richard|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/most-facebook-users-hit-by-cambridge-analytica-scandal-are-californians/|title=Most Facebook users hit by Cambridge Analytica scandal are Californians|date=June 13, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018|publisher=CNET}}</ref> Data was collected on 87 million users while only 270,000 people downloaded the app.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==== Information ====\nFacebook sent a message to those users believed to be affected, saying the information likely included one's \"public profile, page likes, birthday and current city\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Coulter|first=Martin|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/tech/how-to-find-out-if-your-facebook-data-was-shared-with-cambridge-analytica-using-new-tool-launched-by-a3810551.html|title=Find out if your Facebook data was shared with Cambridge Analytica|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> Some of the app's users gave the app permission to access their [[News Feed]], timeline, and messages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/cambridge-analytica-private-facebook-messages/|title=Cambridge Analytica Could Also Access Private Facebook Messages|work=Wired|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> The data was detailed enough for Cambridge Analytica to create [[Psychographics|psychographic]] profiles of the subjects of the data.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" /> The data also included the locations of each person.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" /> For a given political campaign, the data was detailed enough to create a profile which suggested what kind of advertisement would be most effective to persuade a particular person in a particular location for some political event.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" />\n\n==Use of the data==\nPolitical events for which politicians paid Cambridge Analytica to use information from the data breach include the following:\n\n====Ted Cruz campaign====\nIn 2016, Ted Cruz hired Cambridge Analytica to aid [[Ted Cruz 2016 presidential campaign|his presidential campaign]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Federal Election Commission]] reported that Cruz paid the company $5.8 million in services.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/03/20/ted-cruz-campaign-cambridge-analytica/|title=Ted Cruz says Cambridge Analytica told his presidential campaign its data use was legal|last=Samsel|first=Patrick Svitek and Haley|date=2018-03-20|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Although Cambridge Analytica was not well-known at the time, this is when it started to create individual psychographic profiles.<ref name=\":2\" /> This data was then used to create tailored advertisements for each person to sway them into voting for Cruz. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Donald Trump campaign====\n[[Donald Trump]]\u2019s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]] utilized the harvest data to build psychographic profiles, determining users' personality traits based on their Facebook activity.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|date=2018-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole}}</ref> The campaign team used this information as a micro-targeting technique, displaying customized messages about Trump to different US voters on various digital platforms.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Lewis|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/23/leaked-cambridge-analyticas-blueprint-for-trump-victory|title=Leaked: Cambridge Analytica's blueprint for Trump victory|date=2018-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Hilder|first2=Paul|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Ads were segmented into different categories, mainly based on whether individuals were Trump supporters or potential [[Swing vote|swing votes]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Supporters of Trump received triumphant visuals of him, as well as information regarding polling stations.<ref name=\":3\" /> Swing voters were instead often shown images of Trump\u2019s more notable supporters and negative graphics or ideas about his opponent, [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\":3\" /> For example, the collected data was specifically used by \u201cMake America Number 1 Super PAC\u201d to attack Clinton through constructed advertisements that attempted to highlight the corruption of Clinton as a way of propping up Trump as a better candidate for presidency.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2018/mar/21/jack-posopiec/trump-campaign-used-cambridge-analytica-final-mont/|title=PolitiFact - Trump campaign used Cambridge Analytica in final months of campaign|last=Washington|first=District of Columbia 1100 Connecticut Ave NW Suite 1300B|last2=Dc 20036|website=@politifact|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Potential usage in Russia====\nIn 2018, the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] questioned [[SCL Group]] director [[Alexander Nix]] in a hearing about Cambridge Analytica\u2019s connections with Russian oil company, [[Lukoil]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Hakim|first=Danny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-russia.html|title=Data Firm Tied to Trump Campaign Talked Business With Russians|date=2018-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Matthew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nix stated he had no connections to the two companies despite concerns that the oil company was interested in how the company's data was used to target American voters.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cambridge Analytica had become a point of focus in politics since its involvement in Trump's campaign at this point.<ref name=\":0\" /> Democratic officials made it a point of emphasis for improved investigation over concerns of Russian ties with Cambridge Analytica. It was later confirmed by Christopher Wylie that Lukoil was interested in the company\u2019s data regarding political targeting. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\nIn December 2015, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that Cambridge Analytica used the data at the behest of Ted Cruz.<ref name=\"guardian December 20155\" /> According to [[PolitiFact]], Trump paid Cambridge Analytica in September, October, and November for data on Americans and their political preferences.<ref name=\":33\" /> On March 17, 2018, ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' broke the story simultaneously. The Observer worked with [[Christopher Wylie]], a former employee of Cambridge Analytica, for more than a year before bringing in ''The New York Times'' to report the story in the US.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /><ref name=\"NYT original4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-worry-for-facebook-disenchanted-users-1521717883|title=Next Worry for Facebook: Disenchanted Users|last=Grind|first=Kirsten|date=March 22, 2018|website=wsj.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milanofinanza.it/news/e-iniziata-la-grande-fuga-da-zuckerberg-201803232048569102|title=E' iniziata la grande fuga da Zuckerberg|last=Crespi|first=Giorgia|date=March 24, 2018|website=milanofinanza.it|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wyborcza.pl/wiecejswiata/7,163752,23183370,kolejny-problem-facebooka-rozczarowani-uzytkownicy-odchodza.html|title=E' Kolejny problem Facebooka|date=April 23, 2018|website=wyborcza.pl|accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Meghan McCain]] has drawn an equivalence between the use of data by [[Cambridge Analytica]] and [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|Barack Obama's 2012 presidential campaign]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20190220020940/https://www.investors.com/politics/editorials/facebook-data-scandal-trump-election-obama-2012/ Funny, When Obama Harvested Facebook Data On Millions Of Users To Win In 2012, Everyone Cheered]\". ''[[Investor's Business Daily]]''. March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.forbes.com/sites/kalevleetaru/2018/03/19/why-are-we-only-now-talking-about-facebook-and-elections/ Why Are We Only Now Talking About Facebook And Elections?]\". ''[[Forbes]]''. March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.news.com.au/technology/online/security/former-obama-campaign-boss-reveals-how-they-could-access-creepy-facebook-data/news-story/5a275b7c9f540fc9542f5256e644e26e Former Facebook staffer, Obama campaign boss reveal concerns about Facebook data]\". [[News.com.au]]. March 21, 2018.</ref> This data was not used in an unethical way, however, according to [[PolitiFact]]. Obama's campaign used this data to \u201chave their supporters contact their most persuadable friends\u201d rather than using this data for highly targeted digital ads on websites such as Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/mar/22/meghan-mccain/comparing-facebook-data-use-obama-cambridge-analyt/|title=Comparing Facebook data use by Obama, Cambridge Analytica|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|language=en|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal also received media coverage in the form of a 2019 [[Netflix]] documentary, ''[[The Great Hack]]''.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/20/the-great-hack-cambridge-analytica-scandal-facebook-netflix|title=The Great Hack: the film that goes behind the scenes of the Facebook data scandal|date=2019-07-20|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-19|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> This is the first feature-length media piece that ties together the various elements of the scandal through a narrative.<ref name=\":5\" /> The documentary provides information on the background information and events related to Cambridge Analytica, Facebook, and the 2016 election that resulted in the overall data scandal.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/746089858/documentary-the-great-hack|title=Documentary: 'The Great Hack'|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> ''The Great Hack'' communicates the experiences and personal journeys of multiple individuals that were involved in the event in different ways and through different relationships.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> These individuals include David Carroll, [[Brittany Kaiser]], and more.<ref name=\":6\" /> David Carroll is a New York professor in the field of media that attempted to navigate the legal system in order to discover what data Cambridge Analytica had in possession about him.<ref name=\":6\" /> Meanwhile, Brittany Kaiser is a former Cambridge Analytica employee that ultimately became a whistleblower for the data scandal.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Responses==\n\n==== Facebook and other companies ====\nFacebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] first apologized for the situation with Cambridge Analytica on CNN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investors.com/news/technology/facebook-stock-sell-signals-cambridge-analytica-data-scandal/|title=Facebook Stock Troubles Didn't Start With Data Scandal|last=Deagon|first=Brian|date=March 23, 2018|website=Investors Business Daily|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> calling it an \"issue\", a \"mistake\" and a \"breach of trust\". He explained that he was responding to the Facebook community\u2019s concerns and that the company\u2019s initial focus on [[data portability]] had shifted to locking down data; he also reminded the platform\u2019s users of their [[right of access to personal data]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/03/21/technology/mark-zuckerberg-cnn-interview-transcript/index.html|title=Mark Zuckerberg in his own words: The CNN interview|date=2018-03-21|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Other Facebook officials argued against calling it a \"data breach,\" arguing those who took the personality quiz originally consented to give away their information.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/money/5210825/facebook-data-breach-experts/|title=Was Your Facebook Data Actually 'Breached'? Depends On Who You Ask|last=Glum|first=Julia|date=March 22, 2018|work=[[Money (magazine)|Money]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325074027/http://time.com/money/5210825/facebook-data-breach-experts/|archive-date=March 25, 2018|access-date=March 27, 2018|df=}}</ref> Zuckerberg pledged to make changes and reforms in Facebook policy to prevent similar breaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43494337|title=Facebook's Zuckerberg speaks out over Cambridge Analytica 'breach'|last1=Lee|first1=Dave|date=March 22, 2018|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326024945/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43494337|archive-date=March 26, 2018|access-date=March 27, 2018|df=}}</ref> On March 25, 2018, Zuckerberg published a personal letter in various newspapers apologizing on behalf of Facebook.<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenzie|first=Sheena|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/europe/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-sorry-ads-newspapers-intl/index.html|title=Facebook's Zuckerberg says sorry in full-page newspaper ads|date=March 25, 2018|work=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326013941/https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/europe/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-sorry-ads-newspapers-intl/index.html|archive-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> In April, they{{who}} decided to implement the EU's [[General Data Protection Regulation]] in all areas of operation and not just the EU.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rahman|first=Mishaal|url=https://www.xda-developers.com/facebook-voluntarly-enforce-eu-privacy-law/|title=Amidst data scandal, Facebook will voluntarily enforce EU's new privacy rules \"everywhere\"|date=April 4, 2018|work=[[xda-developers]]|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] said that they suspended Cambridge Analytica from using their [[Amazon Web Services]] when they learned that their service was collecting personal information.<ref name=\"Intercept 30 March 20183\">{{cite news|last1=Schwartz|first1=Mattathias|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/03/30/facebook-failed-to-protect-30-million-users-from-having-their-data-harvested-by-trump-campaign-affiliate/|title=Facebook Failed to Protect 30 Million Users From Having Their Data Harvested by Trump Campaign Affiliate|date=March 30, 2017|work=The Intercept|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326152829/https://theintercept.com/2017/03/30/facebook-failed-to-protect-30-million-users-from-having-their-data-harvested-by-trump-campaign-affiliate/|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref> The Italian banking company [[UniCredit]] stopped advertising and marketing on Facebook.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-unicredit/unicredit-has-stopped-using-facebook-for-advertising-ceo-idUSKBN1KS1N5|title=UniCredit has stopped using Facebook for advertising: CEO|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2018, Facebook released their first earnings report since the scandal was reported. Revenue fell since the last quarter, but this is usual as it followed the holiday season quote. The quarter revenue was the highest for a first quarter, and the second overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1262254/facebook-earnings-if-money-is-the-only-thing-that-matters-facebook-is-doing-more-than-fine/|title=Facebook steamrolled over the Cambridge Analytica scandal, posting another record quarter|last=Kozlowska|first=Hanna|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFacebook established [[Social Science One]] as a response to the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialscience.one/our-facebook-partnership|title=Our Facebook Partnership|website=socialscience.one|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Governmental actions ====\nThe governments of India<ref>{{Cite news|last=Team|first=BS Web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/congress-client-of-cambridge-analytica-for-elections-says-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-rahul-gandhi-apologise-bjp-top-10-developments-118032800119_1.html|title=Christopher Wylie names Congress as Cambridge Analytica client; 10 updates|date=March 28, 2018|work=Business Standard India|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.analyticsindiamag.com/it-ministry-notice-facebook-data-leak-cambridge-analytica/|title=Cambridge Analytica Controversy: IT Ministry Issues Notice To Facebook|last=Hebbar|first=Prajakta|date=March 29, 2018|website=Analytics India Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> and Brazil<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-brazil/brazil-prosecutors-open-investigation-into-cambridge-analytica-idUSKBN1GX35A|title=Brazil prosecutors open investigation into Cambridge Analytica|last1=Editorial|first1=Reuters|date=March 21, 2018|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326064259/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-brazil/brazil-prosecutors-open-investigation-into-cambridge-analytica-idUSKBN1GX35A|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-s-brazil-partner-suspends-deal-amid-scandal|title=Cambridge Analytica\u2019s Brazil Partner Asks to Suspend Deal|last1=Biller|first1=David|date=March 21, 2018|website=Bloomberg.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326202429/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-s-brazil-partner-suspends-deal-amid-scandal|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref> demanded that Cambridge Analytica report how anyone used data from the breach in political campaigning, and various regional governments in the United States have lawsuits in their court systems from citizens affected by the data breach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/03/cook-county-illinois-sues-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-over-data-breach/|title=Facebook accused of massive fraud in new lawsuit filed by Cook County|last1=Farivar|first1=Cyrus|date=March 25, 2018|website=[[Ars Technica]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326043603/https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/03/cook-county-illinois-sues-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-over-data-breach/|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn early July 2018, the United Kingdom's [[Information Commissioner's Office]] announced it intended to fine Facebook \u00a3500,000 ($663,000) over the data scandal, this being the maximum fine allowed at the time of the breach, saying Facebook \"contravened the law by failing to safeguard people's information\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/2018/07/10/5c63a730-848b-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Facebook is slapped with the first fine for Cambridge Analytica scandal|date=July 10, 2018|accessdate=May 5, 2019|agency=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, a court filing by the U.S. [[Attorney General for the District of Columbia]] alleged that Facebook knew of Cambridge Analytica's \"improper data-gathering practices\" months before they were first publicly reported in December 2015.<ref name=\"2019-03-22-gu3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/mar/21/facebook-knew-of-cambridge-analytica-data-misuse-earlier-than-reported-court-filing|title=Facebook acknowledges concerns over Cambridge Analytica emerged earlier than reported|last=Wong|first=Julia Carrie|date=2019-03-22|website=the Guardian|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] voted to approve fining Facebook around $5 billion to finally settle the investigation to the scandal, with a 3-2 vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jul/12/facebook-fine-ftc-privacy-violations|title=Facebook to be fined $5bn for Cambridge Analytica privacy violations \u2013 reports {{!}} Facebook {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==== Impact on Facebook users and investors ====\nSince April 2018, the first full month since the breaking of the Cambridge Analytica data scandal, the number of likes, posts and shares on the site had decreased by almost 20%, and has decreased ever since, with the aforementioned activity only momentarily increasing during the summer and during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 US midterm elections]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=editor|first=Alex Hern Technology|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jun/20/facebook-usage-collapsed-since-scandal-data-shows|title=Facebook usage falling after privacy scandals, data suggests|date=2019-06-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Despite this, user growth of the site has increased in the period since the scandal, increasing by 1.8% during the final quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/30/18204186/facebook-q4-2018-earnings-user-growth-revenue-increase-privacy-scandals|title=Facebook keeps growing despite scandals and privacy outrage|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-01-30|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2018, a little after a week after the story was initially published, Facebook stock fell by about 24%, equivalent to $134 billion. By May 10, Wall Street reported that the company recovered their losses. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-stock-price-recovers-all-134-billion-lost-in-after-cambridge-analytica-datascandal/|title=Facebook stock recovers all $134B lost after Cambridge Analytica data scandal|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== #DeleteFacebook movement ====\nThe public reacted to the data privacy breach by initiating the campaign #DeleteFacebook with the aim of starting a movement to boycott Facebook. The hashtag was used almost 90,000 on social media platforms such Instagram, Facebook and Twitter.<ref name=\":4\" /> 93% of the mentions of the hashtag actually appeared on Twitter, making it the main social media platform used to share the hashtag.<ref name=\":4\">Data source: Google Trends (https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=2018-01-01%202020-01-01&geo=US&q=%23deletefacebook)</ref> However, a survey by investment firm Raymond James found that although approximately 84% of Facebook users were concerned about how the app used their data, about 48% of those surveyed claimed they wouldn\u2019t actually cut back on their usage of the social media network.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2018/03/28/people-really-deleting-their-facebook-accounts-its-complicated/464109002/|title=Delete Facebook? It's a lot more complicated than that|last=Guynn|first=Jessica|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Additionally, in 2018 Mark Zuckerberg commented that he didn\u2019t think the company had seen \u201ca meaningful number of people act\u201d on deleting Facebook.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn additional hashtag, #OwnYourData, was coined by Brittany Kaiser. The hashtag was created by Kaiser as a Facebook campaign that pushed for increased transparency on the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/who-brittany-kaiser-ex-cambridge-analytica-director-warns-facebook-leak-much-889609|title=Who is Brittany Kaiser? Cambridge Analytica whistleblower teases new revelations|last=EDT|first=Jason Murdock On 4/17/18 at 12:30 PM|date=2018-04-17|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> #OwnYourData was also used in Kaiser's petition for Facebook to alter their policies and give users increased power and control over their data, which she refers to as users\u2019 assets and property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/07/brittany-kaiser-now-today-age/|title=Brittany Kaiser Now: Where Is She Today & How Old Is She?|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=2019-07-24|website=Heavy.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In addition to the hashtag, Kaiser also created the Own Your Data Foundation to promote increased digital intelligence education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ownyourdata.foundation/|title=Own Your Data Foundation|website=ownyourdata.foundation|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Witness and Expert Testimonies ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2018}}\n\n==== Eitan Hersh ====\nIn 2015, Eitan Hersh published ''Hacking the Electorate: How Campaigns Perceive Voters'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hersh, Eitan|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/921817268|title=Hacking the electorate : how campaigns perceive voters|isbn=978-1-107-10289-7|oclc=921817268}}</ref> which analyzed the databases used for campaigns between 2008 and 2014. On May 6, 2018, Eitan Hersh, a former professor of political science at [[Tufts University]] testified before Congress as an expert on voter targeting.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Hersh%20Testimony1.pdf|title=Eitan Hersh's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHersh claimed that the voter targeting by Cambridge Analytica did not excessively affect the outcome of the 2016 election because the techniques used by Cambridge Analytica were similar to those of presidential campaigns well before 2016. Further, he claimed that the correlation between user \u201clikes\u201d and personality traits were weak and thus the psychological profiling of users were also weak.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n==== Mark Jamison ====\nMark Jamison, the director and Gunter Professor of the Public Utility Research Center at the University of Florida, testified before Congress on May 6, 2018 as an expert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.benton.org/blog/getting-know-mark-jamison-president-elect-trumps-fcc-transition-team-co-leader|title=Getting to Know Mark Jamison, President-elect Trump\u2019s FCC Transition Team Co-Leader|date=2016-12-02|website=Benton Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Jamison reiterated that it was not unusual for presidential campaigns to use data like Facebook\u2019s data to profile voters; Presidents Barack Obama and [[George W. Bush]] also used models to micro-target voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aei.org/press/testimony-aei-tech-scholar-mark-jamison-testifies-today-on-cambridge-analytica-and-the-future-of-data-privacy/|title=AEI Tech Scholar Mark Jamison testifies today on Cambridge Analytica and the future of data privacy|website=American Enterprise Institute - AEI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Jamison criticized Facebook for not being \u201cclear and candid with its users\u201d because the users were not aware of the extent that their data would be used. Jamison finished his testimony by saying that if the federal government were to regulate voter targeting to happen on sites like Facebook, it would harm the users of those sites because it would be too restrictive of those sites and would make things worse for regulators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Jamison%20Testimony.pdf|title=Mark Jamison's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Christopher Wylie ====\nOn May 16, 2018, Christopher Wylie, who is considered the \u201cwhistleblower\u201d on Cambridge Analytica and also served as Cambridge Analytica\u2019s Director of Research in 2013 and 2014, also testified to Congress. He was considered a witness to both British and American authorities, and he claims he decided to whistle-blow to \u201cprotect democratic institutions from rogue actors and hostile foreign interference, as well as ensure the safety of Americans online.\u201d He claimed that at Cambridge Analytica \u201canything goes\u201d and that Cambridge Analytica was \u201ca corrupting force in the world.\u201d He detailed to Congress how Cambridge Analytica used Facebook\u2019s data to categorize people into groups based on political ideology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/10/book-excerpt-mindf-ck-by-christopher-wylie.html|title=How I Helped Hack Democracy|last=Wylie|first=Christopher|date=2019-10-04|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He also claimed that Eitan Hersh contradicted \u201ccopious amounts of peer-reviewed literature in top scientific journals, including the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|Proceedings of the National Academy of Science]], [[Psychological Science]], and Journal of Personality and Individual Differences\u201d by saying that Facebook\u2019s categorizing of people were weak.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Wylie%20Testimony.pdf|title=Christopher Wylie's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nChristopher Wylie also testified about Russian contact with Cambridge Analytica and the campaign, voter disengagement, and his thoughts on Facebook\u2019s response.<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n==== Mark Zuckerberg ====\nDuring his testimony before Congress on April 10, 2018, [[Mark Zuckerberg]] said it was his personal mistake that he did not do enough to prevent Facebook from being used for harm. \u201cThat goes for fake news, foreign interference in elections and hate speech.\u201d During the testimony, Mark Zuckerberg publicly apologized for the breach of private data: \u201cIt was my mistake, and I\u2019m sorry. I started Facebook, I run it, and I\u2019m responsible for what happens here.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/facebook-social-media-privacy-and-the-use-and-abuse-of-data|title=Facebook, Social Media Privacy, and the Use and Abuse of Data {{!}} United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|website=judiciary.senate.gov|language=en|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nZuckerberg said that in 2013 researcher [[Aleksandr Kogan]] from [[Cambridge University]] had created a personality quiz app, which was installed by 300,000 people. The app was then able to retrieve Facebook information, including that of the users' friends, and this was obtained by Kogan. It was not until 2015 that Zuckerberg learned that these users' information was shared by Kogan with [[Cambridge Analytica]]. Cambridge Analytica was subsequently asked to remove all the data. It was later discovered by ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[The New York Times]] and [[Channel 4]] that the data had in fact not been deleted.<ref name=\":023\">{{Cite web|url=http://docs.house.gov/meetings/IF/IF00/20180411/108090/HHRG-115-IF00-Wstate-ZuckerbergM-20180411.pdf|title=Mark Zuckerberg's Written Testimony to the House of Representatives|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Successors==\n\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], a company run by former officials at Cambridge Analytica, [[Data Propria]], has been working for President [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2020|Donald Trump\u2019s 2020 re-election effort]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/96928216bdc341ada659447973a688e4/AP:-Trump-2020-working-with-ex-Cambridge-Analytica-staffers|title=AP: Trump 2020 working with ex-Cambridge Analytica staffers|author=Jeff Horwitz|date=June 15, 2018|work=Associated Press|access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* [[AggregateIQ]]\n* [[BeLeave]]\n* ''[[The Great Hack]]'', 2019 documentary film\n* [[Russian interference in the 2016 Brexit referendum]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/c81zyn0888lt/facebook-cambridge-analytica-data-scandal BBC Coverage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/series/cambridge-analytica-files The Guardian Coverage]\n*[https://www.ted.com/talks/carole_cadwalladr_facebook_s_role_in_brexit_and_the_threat_to_democracy/transcript Carole Cadwalladr @TED2019: Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html?module=inline New York Times Coverage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election The Guardian Article; Revealed]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Corporate scandals}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facebook-Cambridge Analytica data scandal}}\n[[Category:Data breaches]]\n[[Category:Big data]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Analytica]]\n[[Category:Facebook criticisms and controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 scandals]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corporate scandals]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=August 2019}}{{short description|March 2018 scandal involving personal data mining for political purposes}}\n{{Short description|Scandal involving unconsented use of personal information on Facebook for political advertising.}}\n[[File:Cambridge Analytica and Facebook.jpg|thumb|A user of the Cambridge Analytica and Facebook product. ]]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\nThe '''Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal''' was a major scandal in early 2018 where [[Cambridge Analytica]] harvested the personal data of millions of people's [[Facebook]] profiles without their consent and used it for [[Political Advertising|political advertising]]. The scandal has been described as a watershed moment in the public understanding of personal data and precipitated a 17% fall in Facebook's share price and calls for tighter regulation of tech companies' use of personal data.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2018/04/09/why-is-mark-zuckerberg-testifying-in-congress|title=Why is Mark Zuckerberg testifying in Congress?|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-13|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nA data scientist at [[Cambridge University]], [[Aleksandr Kogan]], was hired by Cambridge Analytica, to develop an app called \"This Is Your Digital Life\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hern|first=Alex|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/10/facebook-notify-users-data-harvested-cambridge-analytica|title=How to check whether Facebook shared your data with Cambridge Analytica|date=April 10, 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>{{when}} (sometimes stylized as \"thisisyourdigitallife\").<ref name=\"guardian original4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election|title=Revealed: 50 million Facebook profiles harvested for Cambridge Analytica in major data breach|last1=Graham-Harrison|first1=Emma|last2=Cadwalladr|first2=Carole|date=March 17, 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318001541/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election|archive-date=March 18, 2018|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC News3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-05/facebook-raises-cambridge-analytica-estimates/9620652|title=Facebook says 300,000 Australians may have had their data 'improperly shared'|date=April 5, 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=May 17, 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref> He provided the app to Cambridge Analytica,<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> and Cambridge Analytica in turn arranged an [[informed consent]] process for research in which several hundred thousand Facebook users would agree to complete a survey for payment that was only for academic use.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite news|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/07/the-great-british-brexit-robbery-hijacked-democracy|title=The great British Brexit robbery: how our democracy was hijacked|date=2017-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> However, Facebook allowed this app not only to collect personal information from survey respondents but also from respondents\u2019 Facebook friends.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /> In this way, Cambridge Analytica acquired data from millions of Facebook users.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" />\n\nThe illicit harvesting of [[personal data]] by Cambridge Analytica was first reported in December 2015 by Harry Davies, a journalist for ''[[The Guardian]]''. He reported that Cambridge Analytica was working for United States Senator [[Ted Cruz]] using data harvested from millions of people's Facebook accounts without their consent.<ref name=\"guardian December 20155\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data|title=Ted Cruz campaign using firm that harvested data on millions of unwitting Facebook users|last1=Davies|first1=Harry|date=December 11, 2015|website=the Guardian|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216175150/http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/11/senator-ted-cruz-president-campaign-facebook-user-data|archive-date=February 16, 2016|df=}}</ref> Facebook refused to comment on the story other than to say it was investigating.{{citation needed}} Further reports followed in the Swiss publication ''Das Magazin'' by Hannes Grasseger and Mikael Krogerus (December 2016) (later translated and published by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''),{{citation needed}} [[Carole Cadwalladr]] in ''The Guardian'' (starting in February 2017){{citation needed}} and Mattathias Schwartz in ''[[The Intercept]]'' (March 2017).{{citation needed}} Facebook refused to comment on the claims in any of the articles.{{citation needed}}\n\nThe scandal finally erupted in March 2018 with the emergence of a whistleblower, an ex-Cambridge Analytica employee [[Christopher Wylie]]. He had been an anonymous source for an article in 2017 in ''[[The Observer]]'' by Cadwalladr, headlined \"The Great British [[Brexit]] Robbery\".<ref name=\":04\" /> This article went viral but was disbelieved in some quarters, prompting skeptical responses in ''[[The New York Times]]'' among others.{{citation needed}} Cadwalladr worked with Wylie for a year to coax him to come forward as a whistleblower.{{citation needed}} She later brought in [[Channel 4 News]] in the UK and ''The New York Times'' due to legal threats against ''The Guardian'' and ''The Observer'' by Cambridge Analytica.{{citation needed}}\n\nThe three news organisations{{which}} published simultaneously on March 17, 2018, and caused a huge public outcry.{{citation needed}} More than $100 billion was knocked off Facebook's market capitalization in days{{citation needed}} and politicians in the US and UK demanded answers from Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]]. The scandal eventually led to him agreeing to testify in front of the [[United States Congress]].{{citation needed}}\n\n==Characteristics of the data==\n\n==== Numbers ====\n''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', ''The New York Times'', and ''The Observer'' reported that the data-set had included information on 50 million Facebook users.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/facebook-exposed-87-million-users-to-cambridge-analytica/|title=Facebook Exposed 87 Million Users to Cambridge Analytica|work=Wired|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT original4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matthew|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|date=March 17, 2018|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317131953/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|archive-date=March 17, 2018|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole|df=}}</ref> While Cambridge Analytica claimed it had only collected 30 million Facebook user profiles,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/facebook-send-cambridge-analytica-data-use-notices-monday-n863811|title=Facebook to send Cambridge Analytica data-use notices to 87 million users today|date=April 9, 2018|work=NBC News|accessdate=April 9, 2018|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Facebook later confirmed that it actually had data on potentially over 87 million users,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1245049/the-cambridge-analytica-scandal-affected-87-million-people-facebook-says/|title=The Cambridge Analytica scandal affected 87 million people, Facebook says|last1=Kozlowska|first1=Hanna|date=April 4, 2018|website=Quartz|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> with 70.6 million of those people from the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1245355/outside-us-philippines-saw-most-facebook-user-data-go-to-cambridge-analytica/|title=Outside US, Philippines saw most Facebook user data go to Cambridge Analytica|last1=Horwitz|first1=Josh|date=April 5, 2018|website=Quartz|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> Facebook estimated that [[California]] was the most affected U.S. state, with 6.7 million impacted users, followed by [[Texas]], with 5.6 million, and [[Florida]], with 4.3 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nieva|first=Richard|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/most-facebook-users-hit-by-cambridge-analytica-scandal-are-californians/|title=Most Facebook users hit by Cambridge Analytica scandal are Californians|date=June 13, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018|publisher=CNET}}</ref> Data was collected on 87 million users while only 270,000 people downloaded the app.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n==== Information ====\nFacebook sent a message to those users believed to be affected, saying the information likely included one's \"public profile, page likes, birthday and current city\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Coulter|first=Martin|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/tech/how-to-find-out-if-your-facebook-data-was-shared-with-cambridge-analytica-using-new-tool-launched-by-a3810551.html|title=Find out if your Facebook data was shared with Cambridge Analytica|work=Evening Standard|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> Some of the app's users gave the app permission to access their [[News Feed]], timeline, and messages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/cambridge-analytica-private-facebook-messages/|title=Cambridge Analytica Could Also Access Private Facebook Messages|work=Wired|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> The data was detailed enough for Cambridge Analytica to create [[Psychographics|psychographic]] profiles of the subjects of the data.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" /> The data also included the locations of each person.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" /> For a given political campaign, the data was detailed enough to create a profile which suggested what kind of advertisement would be most effective to persuade a particular person in a particular location for some political event.<ref name=\"NYT original4\" />\n\n==Use of the data==\nPolitical events for which politicians paid Cambridge Analytica to use information from the data breach include the following:\n\n====Ted Cruz campaign====\nIn 2016, Ted Cruz hired Cambridge Analytica to aid [[Ted Cruz 2016 presidential campaign|his presidential campaign]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[Federal Election Commission]] reported that Cruz paid the company $5.8 million in services.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/03/20/ted-cruz-campaign-cambridge-analytica/|title=Ted Cruz says Cambridge Analytica told his presidential campaign its data use was legal|last=Samsel|first=Patrick Svitek and Haley|date=2018-03-20|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Although Cambridge Analytica was not well-known at the time, this is when it started to create individual psychographic profiles.<ref name=\":2\" /> This data was then used to create tailored advertisements for each person to sway them into voting for Cruz. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Donald Trump campaign====\n[[Donald Trump]]\u2019s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]] utilized the harvest data to build psychographic profiles, determining users' personality traits based on their Facebook activity.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html|title=How Trump Consultants Exploited the Facebook Data of Millions|date=2018-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Confessore|first2=Nicholas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cadwalladr|first3=Carole}}</ref> The campaign team used this information as a micro-targeting technique, displaying customized messages about Trump to different US voters on various digital platforms.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Lewis|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/23/leaked-cambridge-analyticas-blueprint-for-trump-victory|title=Leaked: Cambridge Analytica's blueprint for Trump victory|date=2018-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Hilder|first2=Paul|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Ads were segmented into different categories, mainly based on whether individuals were Trump supporters or potential [[Swing vote|swing votes]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Supporters of Trump received triumphant visuals of him, as well as information regarding polling stations.<ref name=\":3\" /> Swing voters were instead often shown images of Trump\u2019s more notable supporters and negative graphics or ideas about his opponent, [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\":3\" /> For example, the collected data was specifically used by \u201cMake America Number 1 Super PAC\u201d to attack Clinton through constructed advertisements that attempted to highlight the corruption of Clinton as a way of propping up Trump as a better candidate for presidency.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2018/mar/21/jack-posopiec/trump-campaign-used-cambridge-analytica-final-mont/|title=PolitiFact - Trump campaign used Cambridge Analytica in final months of campaign|last=Washington|first=District of Columbia 1100 Connecticut Ave NW Suite 1300B|last2=Dc 20036|website=@politifact|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Potential usage in Russia====\nIn 2018, the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] questioned [[SCL Group]] director [[Alexander Nix]] in a hearing about Cambridge Analytica\u2019s connections with Russian oil company, [[Lukoil]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Hakim|first=Danny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-russia.html|title=Data Firm Tied to Trump Campaign Talked Business With Russians|date=2018-03-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Matthew|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nix stated he had no connections to the two companies despite concerns that the oil company was interested in how the company's data was used to target American voters.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cambridge Analytica had become a point of focus in politics since its involvement in Trump's campaign at this point.<ref name=\":0\" /> Democratic officials made it a point of emphasis for improved investigation over concerns of Russian ties with Cambridge Analytica. It was later confirmed by Christopher Wylie that Lukoil was interested in the company\u2019s data regarding political targeting. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\nIn December 2015, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that Cambridge Analytica used the data at the behest of Ted Cruz.<ref name=\"guardian December 20155\" /> According to [[PolitiFact]], Trump paid Cambridge Analytica in September, October, and November for data on Americans and their political preferences.<ref name=\":33\" /> On March 17, 2018, ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' broke the story simultaneously. The Observer worked with [[Christopher Wylie]], a former employee of Cambridge Analytica, for more than a year before bringing in ''The New York Times'' to report the story in the US.<ref name=\"guardian original4\" /><ref name=\"NYT original4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-worry-for-facebook-disenchanted-users-1521717883|title=Next Worry for Facebook: Disenchanted Users|last=Grind|first=Kirsten|date=March 22, 2018|website=wsj.com|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milanofinanza.it/news/e-iniziata-la-grande-fuga-da-zuckerberg-201803232048569102|title=E' iniziata la grande fuga da Zuckerberg|last=Crespi|first=Giorgia|date=March 24, 2018|website=milanofinanza.it|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wyborcza.pl/wiecejswiata/7,163752,23183370,kolejny-problem-facebooka-rozczarowani-uzytkownicy-odchodza.html|title=E' Kolejny problem Facebooka|date=April 23, 2018|website=wyborcza.pl|accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Meghan McCain]] has drawn an equivalence between the use of data by [[Cambridge Analytica]] and [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012|Barack Obama's 2012 presidential campaign]].<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20190220020940/https://www.investors.com/politics/editorials/facebook-data-scandal-trump-election-obama-2012/ Funny, When Obama Harvested Facebook Data On Millions Of Users To Win In 2012, Everyone Cheered]\". ''[[Investor's Business Daily]]''. March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.forbes.com/sites/kalevleetaru/2018/03/19/why-are-we-only-now-talking-about-facebook-and-elections/ Why Are We Only Now Talking About Facebook And Elections?]\". ''[[Forbes]]''. March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.news.com.au/technology/online/security/former-obama-campaign-boss-reveals-how-they-could-access-creepy-facebook-data/news-story/5a275b7c9f540fc9542f5256e644e26e Former Facebook staffer, Obama campaign boss reveal concerns about Facebook data]\". [[News.com.au]]. March 21, 2018.</ref> This data was not used in an unethical way, however, according to [[PolitiFact]]. Obama's campaign used this data to \u201chave their supporters contact their most persuadable friends\u201d rather than using this data for highly targeted digital ads on websites such as Facebook.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/mar/22/meghan-mccain/comparing-facebook-data-use-obama-cambridge-analyt/|title=Comparing Facebook data use by Obama, Cambridge Analytica|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|language=en|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal also received media coverage in the form of a 2019 [[Netflix]] documentary, ''[[The Great Hack]]''.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/20/the-great-hack-cambridge-analytica-scandal-facebook-netflix|title=The Great Hack: the film that goes behind the scenes of the Facebook data scandal|date=2019-07-20|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-19|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> This is the first feature-length media piece that ties together the various elements of the scandal through a narrative.<ref name=\":5\" /> The documentary provides information on the background information and events related to Cambridge Analytica, Facebook, and the 2016 election that resulted in the overall data scandal.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/746089858/documentary-the-great-hack|title=Documentary: 'The Great Hack'|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> ''The Great Hack'' communicates the experiences and personal journeys of multiple individuals that were involved in the event in different ways and through different relationships.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> These individuals include David Carroll, [[Brittany Kaiser]], and more.<ref name=\":6\" /> David Carroll is a New York professor in the field of media that attempted to navigate the legal system in order to discover what data Cambridge Analytica had in possession about him.<ref name=\":6\" /> Meanwhile, Brittany Kaiser is a former Cambridge Analytica employee that ultimately became a whistleblower for the data scandal.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==Responses==\n\n==== Facebook and other companies ====\nFacebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] first apologized for the situation with Cambridge Analytica on CNN,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investors.com/news/technology/facebook-stock-sell-signals-cambridge-analytica-data-scandal/|title=Facebook Stock Troubles Didn't Start With Data Scandal|last=Deagon|first=Brian|date=March 23, 2018|website=Investors Business Daily|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> calling it an \"issue\", a \"mistake\" and a \"breach of trust\". He explained that he was responding to the Facebook community\u2019s concerns and that the company\u2019s initial focus on [[data portability]] had shifted to locking down data; he also reminded the platform\u2019s users of their [[right of access to personal data]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/03/21/technology/mark-zuckerberg-cnn-interview-transcript/index.html|title=Mark Zuckerberg in his own words: The CNN interview|date=2018-03-21|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Other Facebook officials argued against calling it a \"data breach,\" arguing those who took the personality quiz originally consented to give away their information.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/money/5210825/facebook-data-breach-experts/|title=Was Your Facebook Data Actually 'Breached'? Depends On Who You Ask|last=Glum|first=Julia|date=March 22, 2018|work=[[Money (magazine)|Money]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325074027/http://time.com/money/5210825/facebook-data-breach-experts/|archive-date=March 25, 2018|access-date=March 27, 2018|df=}}</ref> Zuckerberg pledged to make changes and reforms in Facebook policy to prevent similar breaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43494337|title=Facebook's Zuckerberg speaks out over Cambridge Analytica 'breach'|last1=Lee|first1=Dave|date=March 22, 2018|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326024945/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43494337|archive-date=March 26, 2018|access-date=March 27, 2018|df=}}</ref> On March 25, 2018, Zuckerberg published a personal letter in various newspapers apologizing on behalf of Facebook.<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenzie|first=Sheena|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/europe/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-sorry-ads-newspapers-intl/index.html|title=Facebook's Zuckerberg says sorry in full-page newspaper ads|date=March 25, 2018|work=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326013941/https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/25/europe/facebook-zuckerberg-cambridge-analytica-sorry-ads-newspapers-intl/index.html|archive-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> In April they decided to implement the EU's [[General Data Protection Regulation]] in all areas of operation and not just the EU.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rahman|first=Mishaal|url=https://www.xda-developers.com/facebook-voluntarly-enforce-eu-privacy-law/|title=Amidst data scandal, Facebook will voluntarily enforce EU's new privacy rules \"everywhere\"|date=April 4, 2018|work=[[xda-developers]]|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] said that they suspended Cambridge Analytica from using their [[Amazon Web Services]] when they learned that their service was collecting personal information.<ref name=\"Intercept 30 March 20183\">{{cite news|last1=Schwartz|first1=Mattathias|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/03/30/facebook-failed-to-protect-30-million-users-from-having-their-data-harvested-by-trump-campaign-affiliate/|title=Facebook Failed to Protect 30 Million Users From Having Their Data Harvested by Trump Campaign Affiliate|date=March 30, 2017|work=The Intercept|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326152829/https://theintercept.com/2017/03/30/facebook-failed-to-protect-30-million-users-from-having-their-data-harvested-by-trump-campaign-affiliate/|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref> The Italian banking company [[UniCredit]] stopped advertising and marketing on Facebook.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-unicredit/unicredit-has-stopped-using-facebook-for-advertising-ceo-idUSKBN1KS1N5|title=UniCredit has stopped using Facebook for advertising: CEO|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018|publisher=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2018, Facebook released their first earnings report since the scandal was reported. Revenue fell since the last quarter, but this is usual as it followed the holiday season quote. The quarter revenue was the highest for a first quarter, and the second overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1262254/facebook-earnings-if-money-is-the-only-thing-that-matters-facebook-is-doing-more-than-fine/|title=Facebook steamrolled over the Cambridge Analytica scandal, posting another record quarter|last=Kozlowska|first=Hanna|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFacebook established [[Social Science One]] as a response to the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialscience.one/our-facebook-partnership|title=Our Facebook Partnership|website=socialscience.one|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Governmental actions ====\nThe governments of India<ref>{{Cite news|last=Team|first=BS Web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/congress-client-of-cambridge-analytica-for-elections-says-whistleblower-christopher-wylie-rahul-gandhi-apologise-bjp-top-10-developments-118032800119_1.html|title=Christopher Wylie names Congress as Cambridge Analytica client; 10 updates|date=March 28, 2018|work=Business Standard India|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.analyticsindiamag.com/it-ministry-notice-facebook-data-leak-cambridge-analytica/|title=Cambridge Analytica Controversy: IT Ministry Issues Notice To Facebook|last=Hebbar|first=Prajakta|date=March 29, 2018|website=Analytics India Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> and Brazil<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-brazil/brazil-prosecutors-open-investigation-into-cambridge-analytica-idUSKBN1GX35A|title=Brazil prosecutors open investigation into Cambridge Analytica|last1=Editorial|first1=Reuters|date=March 21, 2018|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326064259/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-facebook-cambridge-analytica-brazil/brazil-prosecutors-open-investigation-into-cambridge-analytica-idUSKBN1GX35A|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-s-brazil-partner-suspends-deal-amid-scandal|title=Cambridge Analytica\u2019s Brazil Partner Asks to Suspend Deal|last1=Biller|first1=David|date=March 21, 2018|website=Bloomberg.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326202429/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/cambridge-analytica-s-brazil-partner-suspends-deal-amid-scandal|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref> demanded that Cambridge Analytica report how anyone used data from the breach in political campaigning, and various regional governments in the United States have lawsuits in their court systems from citizens affected by the data breach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/03/cook-county-illinois-sues-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-over-data-breach/|title=Facebook accused of massive fraud in new lawsuit filed by Cook County|last1=Farivar|first1=Cyrus|date=March 25, 2018|website=[[Ars Technica]]|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326043603/https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2018/03/cook-county-illinois-sues-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-over-data-breach/|archive-date=March 26, 2018|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn early July 2018, the United Kingdom's [[Information Commissioner's Office]] announced it intended to fine Facebook \u00a3500,000 ($663,000) over the data scandal, this being the maximum fine allowed at the time of the breach, saying Facebook \"contravened the law by failing to safeguard people's information\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/2018/07/10/5c63a730-848b-11e8-8f6c-46cb43e3f306_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Facebook is slapped with the first fine for Cambridge Analytica scandal|date=July 10, 2018|accessdate=May 5, 2019|agency=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, a court filing by the U.S. [[Attorney General for the District of Columbia]] alleged that Facebook knew of Cambridge Analytica's \"improper data-gathering practices\" months before they were first publicly reported in December 2015.<ref name=\"2019-03-22-gu3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/mar/21/facebook-knew-of-cambridge-analytica-data-misuse-earlier-than-reported-court-filing|title=Facebook acknowledges concerns over Cambridge Analytica emerged earlier than reported|last=Wong|first=Julia Carrie|date=2019-03-22|website=the Guardian|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] voted to approve fining Facebook around $5 billion to finally settle the investigation to the scandal, with a 3-2 vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jul/12/facebook-fine-ftc-privacy-violations|title=Facebook to be fined $5bn for Cambridge Analytica privacy violations \u2013 reports {{!}} Facebook {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2019-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==== Impact on Facebook users and investors ====\nSince April 2018, the first full month since the breaking of the Cambridge Analytica data scandal, the number of likes, posts and shares on the site had decreased by almost 20%, and has decreased ever since, with the aforementioned activity only momentarily increasing during the summer and during the [[2018 United States elections|2018 US midterm elections]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=editor|first=Alex Hern Technology|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jun/20/facebook-usage-collapsed-since-scandal-data-shows|title=Facebook usage falling after privacy scandals, data suggests|date=2019-06-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Despite this, user growth of the site has increased in the period since the scandal, increasing by 1.8% during the final quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/30/18204186/facebook-q4-2018-earnings-user-growth-revenue-increase-privacy-scandals|title=Facebook keeps growing despite scandals and privacy outrage|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-01-30|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2018, a little after a week after the story was initially published, Facebook stock fell by about 24%, equivalent to $134 billion. By May 10, Wall Street reported that the company recovered their losses. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/facebook-stock-price-recovers-all-134-billion-lost-in-after-cambridge-analytica-datascandal/|title=Facebook stock recovers all $134B lost after Cambridge Analytica data scandal|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==== #DeleteFacebook movement ====\nThe public reacted to the data privacy breach by initiating the campaign #DeleteFacebook with the aim of starting a movement to boycott Facebook. The hashtag was used almost 90,000 on social media platforms such Instagram, Facebook and Twitter.<ref name=\":4\" /> 93% of the mentions of the hashtag actually appeared on Twitter, making it the main social media platform used to share the hashtag.<ref name=\":4\">Data source: Google Trends (https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=2018-01-01%202020-01-01&geo=US&q=%23deletefacebook)</ref> However, a survey by investment firm Raymond James found that although approximately 84% of Facebook users were concerned about how the app used their data, about 48% of those surveyed claimed they wouldn\u2019t actually cut back on their usage of the social media network.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2018/03/28/people-really-deleting-their-facebook-accounts-its-complicated/464109002/|title=Delete Facebook? It's a lot more complicated than that|last=Guynn|first=Jessica|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Additionally, in 2018 Mark Zuckerberg commented that he didn\u2019t think the company had seen \u201ca meaningful number of people act\u201d on deleting Facebook.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAn additional hashtag, #OwnYourData, was coined by Brittany Kaiser. The hashtag was created by Kaiser as a Facebook campaign that pushed for increased transparency on the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/who-brittany-kaiser-ex-cambridge-analytica-director-warns-facebook-leak-much-889609|title=Who is Brittany Kaiser? Cambridge Analytica whistleblower teases new revelations|last=EDT|first=Jason Murdock On 4/17/18 at 12:30 PM|date=2018-04-17|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> #OwnYourData was also used in Kaiser's petition for Facebook to alter their policies and give users increased power and control over their data, which she refers to as users\u2019 assets and property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2019/07/brittany-kaiser-now-today-age/|title=Brittany Kaiser Now: Where Is She Today & How Old Is She?|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=2019-07-24|website=Heavy.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In addition to the hashtag, Kaiser also created the Own Your Data Foundation to promote increased digital intelligence education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ownyourdata.foundation/|title=Own Your Data Foundation|website=ownyourdata.foundation|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Witness and Expert Testimonies ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2018}}\n\n==== Eitan Hersh ====\nIn 2015, Eitan Hersh published ''Hacking the Electorate: How Campaigns Perceive Voters'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hersh, Eitan|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/921817268|title=Hacking the electorate : how campaigns perceive voters|isbn=978-1-107-10289-7|oclc=921817268}}</ref> which analyzed the databases used for campaigns between 2008 and 2014. On May 6, 2018, Eitan Hersh, a former professor of political science at [[Tufts University]] testified before Congress as an expert on voter targeting.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Hersh%20Testimony1.pdf|title=Eitan Hersh's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHersh claimed that the voter targeting by Cambridge Analytica did not excessively affect the outcome of the 2016 election because the techniques used by Cambridge Analytica were similar to those of presidential campaigns well before 2016. Further, he claimed that the correlation between user \u201clikes\u201d and personality traits were weak and thus the psychological profiling of users were also weak.<ref name=\":42\" />\n\n==== Mark Jamison ====\nMark Jamison, the director and Gunter Professor of the Public Utility Research Center at the University of Florida, testified before Congress on May 6, 2018 as an expert.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.benton.org/blog/getting-know-mark-jamison-president-elect-trumps-fcc-transition-team-co-leader|title=Getting to Know Mark Jamison, President-elect Trump\u2019s FCC Transition Team Co-Leader|date=2016-12-02|website=Benton Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Jamison reiterated that it was not unusual for presidential campaigns to use data like Facebook\u2019s data to profile voters; Presidents Barack Obama and [[George W. Bush]] also used models to micro-target voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aei.org/press/testimony-aei-tech-scholar-mark-jamison-testifies-today-on-cambridge-analytica-and-the-future-of-data-privacy/|title=AEI Tech Scholar Mark Jamison testifies today on Cambridge Analytica and the future of data privacy|website=American Enterprise Institute - AEI|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> Jamison criticized Facebook for not being \u201cclear and candid with its users\u201d because the users were not aware of the extent that their data would be used. Jamison finished his testimony by saying that if the federal government were to regulate voter targeting to happen on sites like Facebook, it would harm the users of those sites because it would be too restrictive of those sites and would make things worse for regulators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Jamison%20Testimony.pdf|title=Mark Jamison's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Christopher Wylie ====\nOn May 16, 2018, Christopher Wylie, who is considered the \u201cwhistleblower\u201d on Cambridge Analytica and also served as Cambridge Analytica\u2019s Director of Research in 2013 and 2014, also testified to Congress. He was considered a witness to both British and American authorities, and he claims he decided to whistle-blow to \u201cprotect democratic institutions from rogue actors and hostile foreign interference, as well as ensure the safety of Americans online.\u201d He claimed that at Cambridge Analytica \u201canything goes\u201d and that Cambridge Analytica was \u201ca corrupting force in the world.\u201d He detailed to Congress how Cambridge Analytica used Facebook\u2019s data to categorize people into groups based on political ideology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/10/book-excerpt-mindf-ck-by-christopher-wylie.html|title=How I Helped Hack Democracy|last=Wylie|first=Christopher|date=2019-10-04|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> He also claimed that Eitan Hersh contradicted \u201ccopious amounts of peer-reviewed literature in top scientific journals, including the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|Proceedings of the National Academy of Science]], [[Psychological Science]], and Journal of Personality and Individual Differences\u201d by saying that Facebook\u2019s categorizing of people were weak.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/05-16-18%20Wylie%20Testimony.pdf|title=Christopher Wylie's Written Testimony to the Senate|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nChristopher Wylie also testified about Russian contact with Cambridge Analytica and the campaign, voter disengagement, and his thoughts on Facebook\u2019s response.<ref name=\":52\" />\n\n==== Mark Zuckerberg ====\nDuring his testimony before Congress on April 10, 2018, [[Mark Zuckerberg]] said it was his personal mistake that he did not do enough to prevent Facebook from being used for harm. \u201cThat goes for fake news, foreign interference in elections and hate speech.\u201d During the testimony, Mark Zuckerberg publicly apologized for the breach of private data: \u201cIt was my mistake, and I\u2019m sorry. I started Facebook, I run it, and I\u2019m responsible for what happens here.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/facebook-social-media-privacy-and-the-use-and-abuse-of-data|title=Facebook, Social Media Privacy, and the Use and Abuse of Data {{!}} United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|website=judiciary.senate.gov|language=en|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nZuckerberg said that in 2013 researcher [[Aleksandr Kogan]] from [[Cambridge University]] had created a personality quiz app, which was installed by 300,000 people. The app was then able to retrieve Facebook information, including that of the users' friends, and this was obtained by Kogan. It was not until 2015 that Zuckerberg learned that these users' information was shared by Kogan with [[Cambridge Analytica]]. Cambridge Analytica was subsequently asked to remove all the data. It was later discovered by ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[The New York Times]] and [[Channel 4]] that the data had in fact not been deleted.<ref name=\":023\">{{Cite web|url=http://docs.house.gov/meetings/IF/IF00/20180411/108090/HHRG-115-IF00-Wstate-ZuckerbergM-20180411.pdf|title=Mark Zuckerberg's Written Testimony to the House of Representatives|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Successors==\n\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], a company run by former officials at Cambridge Analytica, [[Data Propria]], has been working for President [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2020|Donald Trump\u2019s 2020 re-election effort]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/96928216bdc341ada659447973a688e4/AP:-Trump-2020-working-with-ex-Cambridge-Analytica-staffers|title=AP: Trump 2020 working with ex-Cambridge Analytica staffers|author=Jeff Horwitz|date=June 15, 2018|work=Associated Press|access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* [[AggregateIQ]]\n* [[BeLeave]]\n* ''[[The Great Hack]]'', 2019 documentary film\n* [[Russian interference in the 2016 Brexit referendum]]\n* [[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/c81zyn0888lt/facebook-cambridge-analytica-data-scandal BBC Coverage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/series/cambridge-analytica-files The Guardian Coverage]\n*[https://www.ted.com/talks/carole_cadwalladr_facebook_s_role_in_brexit_and_the_threat_to_democracy/transcript Carole Cadwalladr @TED2019: Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/us/politics/cambridge-analytica-trump-campaign.html?module=inline New York Times Coverage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/17/cambridge-analytica-facebook-influence-us-election The Guardian Article; Revealed]\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n{{Corporate scandals}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facebook-Cambridge Analytica data scandal}}\n[[Category:Data breaches]]\n[[Category:Big data]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Analytica]]\n[[Category:Facebook criticisms and controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 scandals]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corporate scandals]]\n", "name_user": "Aitch & Aitch Aitch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResponses:who?", "url_page": "//en